The traditional deal, for the shareholders of an investment bank, was=C2=A0=
that the earnings were risky, but they were high. In boom years, the bank m=
ade a lot of money on mergers-and-acquisition and underwriting fees, doing =
trades for clients in active markets, and perhaps doing a few trades for it=
self. In bad years, the bank =E2=80=A6=C2=A0ideally made a lot of money on =
restructuring and rescue-financing fees, doing trades for clients in volati=
le markets, and perhaps doing a few clever short trades for=C2=A0itself. Bu=
t all of this required good timing and market judgment, and occasionally th=
e bank would mess it up and have a bad year for itself. And the bank ran on=
 a lot of leverage, with a relatively thin cushion of equity capital, so a =
bad year could be very spicy indeed.The modern deal, for the shareholders o=
f a big investment bank, is that the earnings are lower but less risky. In =
the boom years, you still get the M&A and underwriting fees, and you still =
do trades for clients, but you take much less trading risk, and your balanc=
e sheet has much more equity, so your return on equity is lower. Proprietar=
y trading =E2=80=94=C2=A0the bank doing trades for its own account based on=
 its own market judgment =E2=80=94 is frowned upon. In bad years, the lack =
of proprietary trading, the restrained risk-taking and the thicker equity c=
ushion means that the risk of disaster is smaller. Also the bank pays a lot=
 of fines every year for, like,   using cell phones, which creates a drag o=
n returns.Investors always prefer stable recurring revenues to risky one-of=
f revenues, so investment banks have always had an incentive to build and e=
mphasize businesses =E2=80=94=C2=A0like asset management =E2=80=94=C2=A0tha=
t provide steady fees, to diversify away from their core businesses of earn=
ing lumpy M&A fees and making profitable trades. But in the olden days, if =
you could offer investors 20% returns on equity, that was pretty good; =E2=
=80=9Calso we have recurring fees=E2=80=9D was a nice bonus but not essenti=
al. In the modern regime, if you are offering 10% returns on equity, you al=
so really do have to tell them a story about how stable and recurring those=
 returns are.=C2=A0And so Goldman Sachs Group Inc. (disclosure: where I use=
d to work)  had an investor day yesterday where it spent its time trying to=
 convince shareholders that it is boring, in part because boring and stable=
=C2=A0is what shareholders want, but also in part because its return on equ=
ity in 2022 was a boring 10.2%. Goldman=E2=80=99s  target for return on equ=
ity is 14% to 16%, roughly what it is averaging in recent years, but consid=
erably below  the 30+% it was earning in the boom years before the 2008 cri=
sis.The leading focus now is Goldman=E2=80=99s=C2=A0asset and wealth manage=
ment business, the classic source of stable recurring revenues for investme=
nt banks; the first slide in  that segment=E2=80=99s presentation is titled=
 =E2=80=9CLeading Asset and Wealth Management Platform Delivering Durable R=
evenues and Earnings Growth.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CIncreasing Fee-Based Revenue=
s Will Create More Durable Earnings as We Navigate Various Market Cycles=E2=
=80=9D is the headline of another slide. =E2=80=9CThis unit is the make-or-=
break path to getting a higher multiple,=E2=80=9D UBS Group AG banking anal=
yst Brennan Hawken   said to Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Sridhar Natarajan: Investo=
rs want durable earnings, and asset management is the way to give it to the=
m. In the old model, the reason to invest in Goldman Sachs was that it empl=
oyed a lot of people who were good at making investing and trading decision=
s, and you hoped that they=E2=80=99d use that skill to buy stuff for Goldma=
n=C2=A0that would go up, leading directly to profits. In the new model, the=
 reason to invest in Goldman Sachs is that it employs people like that, but=
 it uses their=C2=A0skills to buy stuff=C2=A0for clients=C2=A0and charge th=
ose clients steady management fees.Meanwhile the traditional core business =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0the investment bank, now called Global Banking & Markets =E2=
=80=94  also now emphasizes its =E2=80=9CIncreased Durability of Global Ban=
king & Markets Revenues.=E2=80=9D One thing this means is that financing =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0basically lending to hedge funds against their stock and bon=
d portfolios =E2=80=94=C2=A0is a =E2=80=9Cstrategic priority for GBM,=E2=80=
=9D growing from 12% of revenue in 2013 to 22% in 2022. The traditional mod=
el of an investment bank=E2=80=99s trading business is that clients want to=
 trade stuff, and the bank takes the other sides of those trades; if it is =
good at that business it will make a lot of money, but it is taking market =
risk on every trade. The new model is that clients want to own stuff, and G=
oldman will lend them money against that stuff and collect interest: Instea=
d of using its balance sheet to own assets and take market risk, it will us=
e it to lend against assets, take senior claims on them, and ideally not lo=
se money on any of them. Obviously   you can mess this up too, but in theor=
y a portfolio of secured loans against trading assets should be safer and m=
ore boring than a portfolio of those assets themselves.Also there is now a =
business called =E2=80=9CPlatform Solutions,=E2=80=9D which you might not g=
uess from the name is what Goldman calls retail banking? (Disclosure: I am =
also a retail banking customer.)=C2=A0=E2=80=9CPlatform Solutions=E2=80=9D =
sounds like a tech business, one that makes recurring profits by selling te=
chnology to clients without using a lot of balance sheet. =E2=80=9CEmbeddin=
g digital platforms in our clients=E2=80=99 ecosystems=E2=80=9D is how one =
slide  describes the business, but in practice this means a lot of credit-c=
ard lending, and it=C2=A0 lost money in 2022 due to provisions for credit l=
osses. Goldman is retreating from its retail banking efforts, but in a conf=
using way.=C2=A0Natarajan reports:Chief Executive Officer David Solomon got=
 visibly flustered as analysts pressed him to explain the apparent divergen=
ce between promising to scale up operations such as credit cards and instal=
lment lending, while signaling parts could also be sold.=E2=80=9CThis is an=
 albatross around Goldman=E2=80=99s neck,=E2=80=9D Gerard Cassidy, a bankin=
g analyst with Royal Bank of Canada said of the consumer business in an int=
erview, adding that it was disheartening to hear that it=E2=80=99s not goin=
g to break even until 2025.=E2=80=9CThey could have come out and said we ma=
de an error, we are putting it all up for sale, and it=E2=80=99s egg on our=
 face,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CThey could have said we are committed to =
this business and turn it profitable through organic means. But having a bl=
ended message was a confusing one. Are you going to keep it or are you goin=
g to sell it?=E2=80=9DMy Bloomberg Opinion colleague   Paul Davies writes:W=
hat might be sold is the GreenSky point-of-sale lending arm that focuses on=
 home improvement, which Goldman only bought in a $2.24 billion deal in lat=
e 2021, according to Bloomberg News. That would mark a sharp change of hear=
t on a business that should connect well with other parts of Goldman Sachs:=
 The bank could sell treasury and other services to merchants that use Gree=
nSky, plus it originates raw loans to be repackaged and sold by its fixed-i=
ncome bankers. =C2=A0Goldman=E2=80=99s credit-card books would seem a more =
obvious thing to offload: This is very risky lending in which Goldman has n=
o particular advantage or skill. It might be nice to win partnerships with =
large existing corporate clients who want to issue cards, like Apple Inc. o=
r General Motors Co., but it=E2=80=99s hard to see any connection with othe=
r business Goldman might do for those companies. It is also hard to believe=
 that Goldman could run these card programs more efficiently or profitably =
than more experienced consumer banks.Yes but you can describe the credit-ca=
rd business as =E2=80=9Cembedding digital platforms in our clients=E2=80=99=
 ecosystems.=E2=80=9D
