   =20
      MakerDAO
   =20
 =20
There are three basic ways for a stablecoin to work:=09Some centralized sta=
blecoin issuer sells one stablecoin for $1. It takes the dollar, puts it in=
 a bank account, uses the interest on the bank account to pay for its opera=
tional costs, and promises to redeem each stablecoin for $1. This is the si=
mplest=C2=A0approach, but is more centralized than some people in crypto li=
ke, and=C2=A0it requires you to trust the stablecoin issuer, which is maybe=
 not always a great idea. This is how  Tether (probably) works, as well as =
other big stablecoins like USDC and  BUSD.=09Some stablecoin smart contract=
 lets you deposit $2 worth of Bitcoin or Ethereum or whatever as collateral=
, and gives you back one stablecoin as a loan. The stablecoin is meant to b=
e worth $1. You can repay the loan at any time and get back your collateral=
. If the collateral drops in value while the loan is still outstanding, the=
re is some sort of liquidation mechanism =E2=80=94=C2=A0margin calls, basic=
ally =E2=80=94=C2=A0designed to protect the value of the stablecoin. This o=
ne is more crypto-y, in the sense that it can be done with decentralized im=
mutable code rather than some bank that you trust. But it is also less cryp=
to-y in the sense that it is, like, fractional reserve banking? This busine=
ss of slicing risky claims to engineer a safe tranche that is (you hope) al=
ways worth a dollar  feels like what the traditional financial system does,=
 sometimes with bad results. But anyway this sort of thinking is what is be=
hind  MakerDAO=E2=80=99s DAI stablecoin.=C2=A0=09Same as No. 2, except that=
 instead of depositing Bitcoin or Ether or whatever, you deposit $2 worth o=
f some token made up by the person who made up the stablecoin. =E2=80=9CI w=
ill sell you a thing that will always be worth $1,=E2=80=9D some impresario=
 says, =E2=80=9Cbecause it can always be exchanged for $1 worth of bleebits=
, and I can print as many bleebits as I want, because they are just a thing=
 I made up. So I can always pay you $1 worth of bleebits, the math is unass=
ailable.=E2=80=9D This is a real thing that people keep trying, generally w=
ith hilarious results. The  most hilarious was Terra =E2=80=94=C2=A0there, =
the stablecoin was called TerraUSD (or UST) and the bleebits were called Lu=
na =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is a well-known source of chaos. The problem is th=
at some guy just made up the bleebits! If the bleebits are worth $0.01 each=
, then he can give you 100 bleebits for your stablecoin and the math checks=
 out. If they=E2=80=99re worth $0.005 each, he can give you 200 bleebits, f=
ine. If they=E2=80=99re worth=C2=A0zero dollars because they are just a thi=
ng that he made up, you have a divide-by-zero error. In practice what happe=
ns here is that (1) people think the bleebits are valuable, (2) money piles=
 into the stablecoin, (3) somebody looks down and realizes there=E2=80=99s =
nothing there, (4) they sell the stablecoin for bleebits and dump the bleeb=
its, (5) the price collapses, (6) death spiral.The thing to notice is that =
Stablecoin 2 and Stablecoin=C2=A03 are not=C2=A0that=C2=A0different.=C2=A0B=
itcoin=C2=A0is also a thing that someone just made up. It=E2=80=99s just th=
at the person who made up Bitcoin is not the same person who made up MakerD=
AO; the stablecoin uses a somewhat uncorrelated asset as collateral. In Sta=
blecoin 3, the collateral for the stablecoin is basically =E2=80=9Cconfiden=
ce in the stablecoin,=E2=80=9D and when that fails there=E2=80=99s nothing =
left.The people who made Terra were =E2=80=94=C2=A0for all their failings =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0not unaware of this problem. The theory of Terra was roughly=
:=09Issue a stablecoin (TerraUSD) backed by a thing (Luna) they just made u=
p.=09Get people to adopt Luna (allegedly by  lying about its use in a Korea=
n payments app, but never mind that), so that Luna becomes valuable and Ter=
raUSD=E2=80=99s peg to the dollar can be maintained.=09Sell a bunch of Luna=
 to raise cash.=09Invest the cash in stuff =E2=80=94=C2=A0Bitcoin, Treasury=
 bonds, gold =E2=80=94=C2=A0that can be used to back TerraUSD.=09Eventually=
 TerraUSD migrates from Stablecoin 3 (collateralized by stuff they made up)=
 to Stablecoin 1 (there=E2=80=99s a bank account that can be used to redeem=
 all the stablecoins).This did not work, because TerraUSD and Luna crashed =
before they could reach Stage 5. But it was a pleasing=C2=A0idea. Before th=
e crash,  I described it like this: =E2=80=9CThe basic structure of the tra=
de is (1) Ponzi, (2) acceptance, (3) diversification, (4) permanence.=E2=80=
=9D But you could try other paths.=C2=A0I got an email from Sam Kazemian, t=
he founder of the Frax stablecoin, who  described=C2=A0his=C2=A0stablecoin=
=E2=80=99s planned evolution=C2=A0as =E2=80=9C1.) not-ponzi, 100% backed no=
rmal bank 2.) acceptance, slowly unbacking 3.) permanence 4.) THEN finally =
ponzi like the Fed/USD.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=C2=A0I thought this was a very funny=
 email.Other paths are possible. Why not from Stablecoin 2 to Stablecoin 3,=
 for instance? The idea is:=09You do the smart contract thing, where each $=
1 stablecoin is backed by $2 worth of real-ish crypto, Bitcoin or Ether or =
whatever.=09You issue a token for your smart-contract ecosystem, one that g=
ives holders some governance and/or economic rights to that system =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0basically, a sort of=C2=A0stock=C2=A0in your smart-contracts-for-s=
tablecoins protocol.=09As your protocol becomes popular and people put a lo=
t of crypto into it and its stablecoin becomes widely used, the governance =
token becomes more valuable.=09You say =E2=80=9Chey, this governance token =
is pretty valuable, you could put $2 of it into the smart contract and get =
back a $1 stablecoin.=E2=80=9DDoes lending against your own  equity-like to=
ken pretty much always  end in disaster? Oh, sure. But maybe you will make =
it work!Anyway here=E2=80=99s an article from the Defiant titled =E2=80=9CM=
akerDAO=E2=80=99s Plan To Enable MKR As Collateral For DAI Draws Comparison=
s To UST=E2=80=9D:A potential change to one of DeFi=E2=80=99s oldest and la=
rgest protocols is raising concerns in the crypto community.One facet of Ma=
kerDAO=E2=80=99s proposed overhaul would allow users to borrow its DAI stab=
lecoin against its MKR governance token.=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s devastatingly=
 disappointing to see Maker=E2=80=99s co-founder pushing this plan,=E2=80=
=9D PaperImperium, a self-described =E2=80=9Cgovernance liaison, wrote on T=
witter. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s as if nothing was learned this cycle.=E2=80=
=9DMaker is DeFi=E2=80=99s largest lending protocol, with over $6B in total=
 value locked (TVL). It allows people to mint the DAI stablecoin against ma=
jor crypto assets like Ether and Ethereum-based Bitcoin.Noticeably missing =
from the set of supported collateral assets so far has been MKR, Maker=E2=
=80=99s governance token. Some would say this omission is for good reason =
=E2=80=94 governance tokens tend to be much more volatile and illiquid than=
 assets like ETH and BTC, raising the risk of so-called =E2=80=98bank runs=
=E2=80=99 that have driven many a stablecoin into the ground.Allowing users=
 to borrow DAI against MKR could be considered similar to the mechanism beh=
ind Terra=E2=80=99s ill-fated UST stablecoin, which spectacularly collapsed=
 last May, torching over $40B of market value.Hahaha yeah, yeah.
