, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Goldman</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The traditional deal, for the sharehol=
ders of an investment bank, was=C2=A0that the earnings were risky, but they=
 were high. In boom years, the bank made a lot of money on mergers-and-acqu=
isition and underwriting fees, doing trades for clients in active markets, =
and perhaps doing a few trades for itself. In bad years, the bank =E2=80=A6=
=C2=A0ideally made a lot of money on restructuring and rescue-financing fee=
s, doing trades for clients in volatile markets, and perhaps doing a few cl=
ever short trades for=C2=A0itself. But all of this required good timing and=
 market judgment, and occasionally the bank would mess it up and have a bad=
 year for itself. And the bank ran on a lot of leverage, with a relatively =
thin cushion of equity capital, so a bad year could be very spicy indeed.</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The modern deal, for the shareholders of a b=
ig investment bank, is that the earnings are lower but less risky. In the b=
oom years, you still get the M&amp;A and underwriting fees, and you still d=
o trades for clients, but you take much less trading risk, and your balance=
 sheet has much more equity, so your return on equity is lower. Proprietary=
 trading =E2=80=94=C2=A0the bank doing trades for its own account based on =
its own market judgment =E2=80=94 is frowned upon. In bad years, the lack o=
f proprietary trading, the restrained risk-taking and the thicker equity cu=
shion means that the risk of disaster is smaller. Also the bank pays a lot =
of fines every year for, like, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/30698374.259422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2=
FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMDIvdGhlLXNlYy13YW50cy10by1zZWUtbW9yZS1waG9uZXM_Y21wa=
WQ9QkJEMDMwMTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3Ns=
ZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMzAxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cB734a69ad" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">  using cell phones</a>, which creates a drag=
 on returns.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Investors always prefer stable=
 recurring revenues to risky one-off revenues, so investment banks have alw=
ays had an incentive to build and emphasize businesses =E2=80=94=C2=A0like =
asset management =E2=80=94=C2=A0that provide steady fees, to diversify away=
 from their core businesses of earning lumpy M&amp;A fees and making profit=
able trades. But in the olden days, if you could offer investors 20% return=
s on equity, that was pretty good; =E2=80=9Calso we have recurring fees=E2=
=80=9D was a nice bonus but not essential. In the modern regime, if you are=
 offering 10% returns on equity, you also really do have to tell them a sto=
ry about how stable and recurring those returns are.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">And so Goldman Sachs Group Inc. (disclosure: where I used t=
o work) <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30698374.2=
59422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29sZG1hbnNhY2hzLmNvbS9pbnZlc3Rvci1yZWxhdGlvbnMvaW52Z=
XN0b3ItZGF5LTIwMjMvaW5kZXguaHRtbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0ad48801" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
"> had an investor day yesterday</a> where it spent its time trying to conv=
ince shareholders that it is boring, in part because boring and stable=C2=
=A0is what shareholders want, but also in part because its return on equity=
 in 2022 was a boring 10.2%. Goldman=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30698374.259422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29sZG1hbnNhY2=
hzLmNvbS9pbnZlc3Rvci1yZWxhdGlvbnMvaW52ZXN0b3ItZGF5LTIwMjMvbXVsdGltZWRpYS9wc=
mVzZW50YXRpb25zL3BkZnMvc3RhdGUtb2YtdGhlLWZyYW5jaGlzZS5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB632558b6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;"> target</a> for return on equity is 14% to 16%, =
roughly what it is averaging in recent years, but considerably below <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30698374.259422/aHR0cHM6=
