=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
  Paul Davies writes</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What =
might be sold is the GreenSky point-of-sale lending arm that focuses on hom=
e improvement, which Goldman only bought in a $2.24 billion deal in late 20=
21, according to Bloomberg News. That would mark a sharp change of heart on=
 a business that should connect well with other parts of Goldman Sachs: The=
 bank could sell treasury and other services to merchants that use GreenSky=
, plus it originates raw loans to be repackaged and sold by its fixed-incom=
e bankers. =C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Goldman=E2=80=99s credit-=
card books would seem a more obvious thing to offload: This is very risky l=
ending in which Goldman has no particular advantage or skill. It might be n=
ice to win partnerships with large existing corporate clients who want to i=
ssue cards, like Apple Inc. or General Motors Co., but it=E2=80=99s hard to=
 see any connection with other business Goldman might do for those companie=
s. It is also hard to believe that Goldman could run these card programs mo=
re efficiently or profitably than more experienced consumer banks.</p></blo=
ckquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yes but you can describe the credit-ca=
