<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Nice trees we have here, shame if anything were to happen to them</h2=
>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The economics of producing stuff are b=
asically pretty simple. Each thing you produce, you sell to someone for mon=
ey, and the more you produce and sell, the more money you make.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The economics of=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>producing stuf=
f are considerably more metaphysical. There is, in the world, <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30698374.259422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDQtMjEveW91LWNhbi1zZWxsLX=
RoZS10cmVlcy15b3UtZG9uLXQtY3V0P2NtcGlkPUJCRDAzMDEyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZ=
WRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDMwMSZ1dG1fY2Ft=
cGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB77b20877" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  a busin=
ess of=C2=A0<em>not cutting down trees</em></a>. Trees capture carbon, whic=
h is good for the climate, and through various mechanisms =E2=80=94 environ=
mental, social and governance investing; shareholder pressure for net-zero =
emissions; carbon-credit trading markets, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0people can ge=
t paid for not cutting down trees. But there are problems of measurement. T=
here are right now, in the world, absolutely billions of trees that I have =
not cut down, but nobody is paying me for my restraint. Practically speakin=
g, to get paid for not cutting down trees, you have to (1) have the right t=
o cut down the trees and (2) have some <em>propensity=C2=A0</em>for cutting=
 down the trees. Nobody is going around offering me cash for not cutting do=
wn the trees in my backyard, not only for reasons of scale but also because=
 no one expects me to cut them down. But lumber companies can get paid for =
not cutting down trees, because they are in the business of cutting down tr=
ees, so paying them to stop makes a kind of sense.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">Similarly, countries that have vast rainforests that are shri=
nking each day due to uncontrolled logging can probably get paid to stop th=
at, while countries that have vast rainforests that are pretty well protect=
ed have a harder time getting paid. If you are a country that has done a go=
od job of protecting your rainforests, you might feel a bit ill-used by tha=
t. You might call up an <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/30698374.259422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljb=
GVzLzIwMjItMTEtMTUvbWF0dC1sZXZpbmUtcy1tb25leS1zdHVmZi1iaW5hbmNlLWZ0eC1hbmQt=
Y2Fycz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzAxMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3V=
yY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAzMDEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB57c969b1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  ESG Consultant But Evil</a> and =
say, well, how do we get paid for not cutting down our trees? And the ESG C=
onsultant But Evil will give you the obvious advice, which is: Make a big s=
how of cutting down some trees, put them in a wood chipper, put the chips i=
n envelopes and send them to various international bodies and ESG investors=
 with ransom notes saying =E2=80=9Cif you ever want to see these forests ag=
ain pay up.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you pay ransoms to =
kidnappers you will get more kidnapping. If you pay people for not doing th=
ings that they might otherwise do, they will look for ways to credibly thre=
aten to do the things, so they can get paid not to.</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s more or less the=C2=A0experience of Gabon, with =E2=
=80=9Cone of the world=E2=80=99s largest intact rainforests.=E2=80=9D Bloom=
berg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/30698374.259422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9mZWF0dXJlcy8yMDIzLWdhY=
m9uLXJhaW5mb3Jlc3RzLWNhcmJvbi1jcmVkaXRzLz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzAxMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVG=
RiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAzMDE=
mdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB04af264f" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
>Antony Sguazzin and Natasha White report</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">Unlike some of its neighbors, the country strictly limits l=
ogging, palm oil production and other activities that lead to forest destru=
ction; it's suffered less than 1% forest loss since 1990, compared with abo=
ut 14% for continental Africa.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now that oil=
 production, the country=E2=80=99s primary source of revenue, is dwindling,=
 leaders are reevaluating the money-making potential of the forests. Openin=
g more land to timber companies is one option, but for now Gabon=E2=80=99s =
environmentally minded government is more interested in keeping the trees a=
live=E2=80=94if the international financial markets can make it worthwhile.=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The best avenue for that, Gabon says, is t=
he $2 billion-and-growing market for =E2=80=9Ccarbon offsets.=E2=80=9D That=
=E2=80=99s traditionally been limited to those who can document improvement=
 on past environmental practices, not those who, like Gabon, never wrecked =
their forests in the first place. That=E2=80=99s because for a carbon offse=
t to fulfill its function of compensating for its buyer=E2=80=99s emissions=
, it needs to have financed something that wouldn=E2=80=99t have happened o=
therwise. But in Gabon, forest protection has been happening anyway.</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still, Gabon insists it should be compensated for=
 the air-purifying service its trees provide. Otherwise, it hints, its comm=
itment to forest preservation may take a backseat to more traditional econo=
mic development. In its recent national action plan under the Paris Agreeme=
nt, the global climate pact, the country says it plans to remain a =E2=80=
=9Cnet-carbon absorber=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94if it gets access to international =
finance through a carbon market.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CT=
here is no financial instrument to support Gabon to continue to offer this =
critical ecosystem service,=E2=80=9D Akim Daouda, the chief executive offic=
er of Gabon=E2=80=99s $1.9 billion sovereign wealth fund, said in an interv=
iew during a recent trip to London. =E2=80=9CCan we monetize the forest and=
 keep it for the rest of the planet? Or do we need to find a way to respond=
 to the needs of our population?=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">Yes that is absolutely the way you make that threat.</p><table =
